AB Suppose that a firm in charge of a business ecosystem is a firm in
   charge of a microeconomy. To achieve the highest growth rate, how open
   should that economy be? To encourage third-party developers, how long
   should their intellectual property interests last? We develop a
   sequential innovation model that addresses the trade-offs inherent in
   these two decisions: (i) Closing the platform increases the sponsor's
   ability to charge for access, while opening the platform increases
   developer ability to build upon it. (ii) The longer third-party
   developers retain rights to their innovations, the higher the royalties
   they and the sponsor earn, but the sooner those developers' rights
   expire, the sooner their innovations become a public good upon which
   other developers can build. Our model allows us to characterize the
   optimal levels of openness and of intellectual property (IP) duration in
   a platform ecosystem. We use standard Cobb-Douglas production
   technologies to derive our results. These findings can inform innovation
   strategy, choice of organizational form, IP noncompete decisions, and
   regulation policy.
