AB This study examines how characteristics of an interfirm labor-flow
   network affect firm productivity. Using employee job histories to trace
   labor movement between organizations, we construct labor-flow networks
   for both information technology (IT) and non-IT labor and analyze how a
   firm's network structure for the two types of labor affects its
   performance. We find that hiring IT workers from a structurally diverse
   network of firms can substantially improve firm productivity, but that
   the same is not true for non-IT labor, where we find little benefit of
   network diversity. We hypothesize that these results reflect differences
   in the types of knowledge diffusion facilitated by different types of
   labor flows, with IT labor enabling the transfer of new and innovative
   firm practices, which benefits from diversity, while non-IT labor flows
   are more closely associated with implementation of complementary
   organizational practices, which may benefit from a critical mass of
   workers with a common knowledge base. Together, these results
   demonstrate the importance of incorporating a network perspective in
   understanding the full impact of spillover effects from organizational
   hiring activities.
