   store, we show that ignoring regret factors causes the markdown retailer
   to leave up to 20% of its profits on the table. In addition, in a
   competitive market, the markdown retailer rations too aggressively when
   regret is ignored and, as a result, leaves some of the forgone profit to
   its competitor-the EDLP retailer. The retail industry is often
   characterized by its slim profit margins. In such an environment, the
   aforementioned results also suggest that retailers should seriously
   consider investing in developing the capacity to estimate and quantify
   the role of regret in consumers' purchase decisions.
