   behaviors affect channel contracting? We study the problem in a
   bilateral channel where the retailer has private information on evolving
   market conditions. We characterize the optimal contract under arbitrary
   market evolution. The central notion is market inertia: it prices
   retailer's information advantage, dictates price and quantity response
   over time, and determines the contract complexity. Using market inertia,
   we identify a general property-stochastic linearity-that justifies the
   use of simple contracts for a much larger class of channel conditions.
