   relative costs of different products or activities. This handicaps the
   principal when the principal seeks to adjust the product mix. Our main
   conceptual finding is that there is "mix stickiness." The agent's
   superior information about the relative costs of different products or
   activities leads to an advantage for the status quo; that is, there is
   inertia (or stickiness) in the mix of products or activities pursued.
