   reveal its ethical commitment to its contracting partner anytime during
   the contractual relationship. Thus, a commitment to ethics, while of
   course being morally desirable, can lead to higher profits than the
   unbridled profit-maximization of classical economics. We also prove that
   ethics is foundational to both intellectual property (IP) sharing and
   reputation effects, two well-known facilitators of IT outsourcing. In
   fact, the mere possibility of ethical firms (a) forces across-the-board
   IP sharing even if it lowers profits and (b) induces even an ethically
   unconstrained firm to invest in developing a reputation for ethics. Our
   model provides a novel explanation, rooted in ethics, for why IT
   outsourcing is booming despite the formidable impediments of incomplete
   contracts, moral hazard, and adverse selection.
